      static boolean showOnPage(WebElement element, java.lang.String... optional)
      Try to show the webelement on the browser's page.
      First, try to see if the web-element is already shown on page, if not shown on the page
      then it will try to move the web-element to show it on page.
      Finally, if the passed in parameter verify is true, it will return true only if the element is shown on the page;
      if the passed in parameter verify is false, it will always return true.

      • enableClickListenerFailures

        public static boolean enableClickListenerFailures
        Default true. Set to true if we want an Exception to be thrown when we perform a Click and attempt to verify through event listeners that the Click actually happened. The problem is, that so many Click verifications fail due to the page and or WebElement going stale or being overwritten that Click verifications issue failures even though the Click was successful.

        Set to 'false' when you wish to avoid these types of failures.

      • click

        public static void click(WebElement clickable,
         java.awt.Point offset,
         Keys specialKey,
         int mouseButtonNumber)
                  throws SeleniumPlusException
        Click the WebElement at a certain coordination with a special key pressed.
        Firstly it will try to get webelement's location and use Robot to click. At the same
        time, it will listen to a 'javascript mouse down' event to find out if the click really
        happened; If not, it will try to use Selenium's API to do the work.
        Parameters:
        clickable - WebElement, the WebElement to click on
        offset - Point, the coordination relative to this WebElement to click at.
        if the offset is null, then click at the center.
        specialKey - Keys, the special key to press during the click
        mouseButtonNumber - int, the mouse-button-number representing right, middle, or left button. it can be MOUSE_BUTTON_LEFT or MOUSE_BUTTON_RIGHT.
        MOUSE_BUTTON_MIDDLE NOT supported yet.
        Throws:
        SeleniumPlusException

      • doubleClick

        public static void doubleClick(WebElement clickable,
               java.awt.Point offset,
               Keys specialKey,
               int mouseButtonNumber)
                        throws SeleniumPlusException
        Double-Click the WebElement at a certain coordination with a special key pressed.
        Firstly it will try to get webelement's location and use Robot to double click. At the same
        time, it will listen to a 'javascript mouse down' event to find out if the double click really
        happened; If not, it will try to use Selenium's API to do the work.
        Parameters:
        clickable - WebElement, the WebElement to click on
        offset - Point, the coordination relative to this WebElement to click at.
        if the offset is null, then click at the center.
        specialKey - Keys, the special key to presse during the click
        mouseButtonNumber - int, the mouse-button-number representing right, middle, or left button. it can be MOUSE_BUTTON_LEFT
        MOUSE_BUTTON_MIDDLE and MOUSE_BUTTON_RIGHT NOT supported yet.
        Throws:
        SeleniumPlusException

      • inputKeysSAFS2Selenium

        public static void inputKeysSAFS2Selenium(WebElement we,
                          java.lang.String keystrokes)
                                   throws SeleniumPlusException
        Does NOT clear any existing text in the control, but does attempt to insure the window/control has focus.
        Purpose: inputKeys

        Bypasses attempts to use AWT Robot for keystrokes. Attempts to convert SAFS keystrokes to Selenium low-level Actions keystrokes.

        Parameters:
        we - WebElement to send SAFS keystrokes (or plain text).
        keystrokes - SAFS keystrokes or plain text to type.
        Throws:
        SeleniumPlusException - if we are unable to process the keystrokes successfully.

        Does NOT clear any existing text in the control, but does attempt to insure the window/control has focus.

      • showOnPage

        public static boolean showOnPage(WebElement element,
                 java.lang.String... optional)
        Try to show the webelement on the browser's page.
        First, try to see if the web-element is already shown on page, if not shown on the page
        then it will try to move the web-element to show it on page.
        Finally, if the passed in parameter verify is true, it will return true only if the element is shown on the page;
        if the passed in parameter verify is false, it will always return true.
        Parameters:
        element - WebElement, the webelement to show.
        params - optional
          optionals[0] verify boolean, verify that the component is shown on page. The default value is false.
        Returns:
        boolean, true if succeed
